 {"id":"bd-qhnxc","title":"[HIGH] pthread_cancel on a running deferred-cancel thread deterministically SIGABRTs the process","description":"## Symptom

Running just the pthread ABI integration tests deterministically SIGABRTs the test binary at test cancel_running_thread, even under --test-threads=1:

    rch exec -- env CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/rch_target_frankenlibc_cc         cargo test -p frankenlibc-abi --test pthread_abi_test -- --test-threads=1 --nocapture

    running 180 tests
    test atfork_register_succeeds ... ok
    ...
    test cancel_register_unregister_stubs ... ok
    error: test failed, to rerun pass -p frankenlibc-abi --test pthread_abi_test
    process didn't exit successfully: .../pthread_abi_test-... (signal: 6, SIGABRT: process abort signal)
    test cancel_running_thread ...

The abort fires inside cancel_running_thread before the test-harness writes its ok/FAIL line. Repro rate: 100 percent, same result under default parallelism and --test-threads=1.

## Test body

crates/frankenlibc-abi/tests/pthread_abi_test.rs:3943

    fn cancel_running_thread() {
        unsafe {
            let mut thr: libc::pthread_t = 0;
            let rc = pthread_create(&mut thr, ptr::null(),
                Some(cancellable_thread), ptr::null_mut());
            assert_eq!(rc, 0);
            std::thread::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_millis(20));
            let rc = pthread_cancel(thr);
            assert_eq!(rc, 0);
            let mut retval: *mut c_void = ptr::null_mut();
            assert_eq!(pthread_join(thr, &mut retval), 0);
            assert_eq!(retval as usize, !0usize);
        }
    }

The victim-thread body (cancellable_thread at pthread_abi_test.rs:~3925) sets its cancel state ENABLE + type DEFERRED, publishes ready, then sleeps 200ms. The main thread waits 20ms, then pthread_cancels it.

## Diagnosis

The expected sequence is:

1. victim thread installs DEFERRED cancel state and sleeps in a cancellation point (std thread sleep compiles to nanosleep which is a libc-documented cancellation point).
2. pthread_cancel posts the cancel request.
3. victim thread notices the pending cancel at the next cancellation-point check, unwinds with PTHREAD_CANCELED, and pthread_join returns the !0usize sentinel.

The SIGABRT at this site almost certainly means one of:

- pthread_cancel delivered via a signal (SIGCANCEL / 32) but our signal handler installation did not route correctly, so glibc's default action for SIGCANCEL fired (which is Term / Core).
- pthread_exit path in the cancelled thread trips an assertion in our TLS-dtor / stack-unwind code (we recently landed a581f0ac isolating TLS dtor state, this may have introduced a new abort in the cancel-unwind path).
- pthread_cancel invokes libc free on an internal struct allocated through a different allocator, hitting the same free(): invalid size pattern as bd-g2bd5 / bd-ye0f4 but on the cancel path instead of TLS dtors.

## Fix direction

1. Rerun with MALLOC_CHECK_=2 RUST_BACKTRACE=1 cargo test -- --test-threads=1 cancel_running_thread to capture the glibc backtrace at the abort.
2. Compare against the output of the adjacent 'cancel_register_unregister_stubs' (which passes) — difference is only whether a thread actually runs.
3. Audit pthread_cancel in crates/frankenlibc-abi/src/pthread_abi.rs for the signal-based cancel path. Verify the SIGCANCEL handler is installed before pthread_cancel fires.

## Blast radius

cargo test --workspace --all-targets now fails at this test on isolated pthread runs (previously it only failed on parallel glibc_internal_abi_test runs per bd-g2bd5/bd-ye0f4). Serial-mode was our known workaround; this one defeats it.

